Let $\Gamma$ be a non-uniform lattice of $PSL(2,\mathbb{C})$. To every representation $\rho:\Gamma
\rightarrow PSL(n,\mathbb{C})$ it is possible to associate a numerical invariant $\beta_n(\rho)$,
called Borel invariant, which is constant on the $PSL(n,\mathbb{C})$-conjugancy class of the
representation $\rho$ and hence defines a function on the character variety $X(\Gamma,PSL(n,\mathbb{C}))$.
This function is continuous with respect to the topology of the pointwise convergence and it satisfies
a strong rigidity property: it holds $|\beta_n(\rho)|\leq \frac{1}{6}n(n^2-1)\text{Vol}(\Gamma
\backslash \mathbb{H}^3)$ for every representation $\rho:\Gamma \rightarrow PSL(n,\mathbb{C})$
and we have the equality if and only if the representation $\rho$ is conjugated either to $\pi_n \circ
i$ or to $\overline{\pi_n \circ i}$, where $i:\Gamma \rightarrow PSL(2,\mathbb{C})$ is the standard
lattice embedding and $\pi_n:PSL(2,\mathbb{C}) \rightarrow PSL(n,\mathbb{C})$ is the irreducible
representation. We partially answer to a conjecture proposed by Guilloux when $\Gamma$ the reflection
group associated to a regular ideal tetrahedron. More precisely let $\Gamma_0<PSL(2,\mathbb{C})$
be a torsion-free subgroup of $\Gamma$ and let $\rho_k:\Gamma_0 \rightarrow PSL(n,\mathbb{C})$
be a sequence of asymptotically maximal representations, that is $\lim_{k \to \infty} \beta_n(\rho_k)=\frac{1}{6}n(n^2-1)\text{Vol}(\Gamma_0
\backslash \mathbb{H}^3)$. Assume there exists a measurable map $\varphi_k:\mathbb{P}^1(\mathbb{C})
\rightarrow \mathscr{F}(n,\mathbb{C})$ which is $\rho_k$-equivariant. We prove that there
must exists a sequence $(g_k)_{k \in \mathbb{N}}$ where $g_k \in PSL(n,\mathbb{C})$ such that
$\lim_{k \to \infty} g_k \rho_k(\gamma) g_k^{-1}=(\pi_n \circ i)(\gamma)$, for every $\gamma
\in \Gamma_0$. 